A̱lyem '''Tyap''' ka yet sot zwályiat [[lilyem Pi̱lato]] jhyang kya ka̱ byia̱ a̱tsatsak shi di̱ fam-a̱byin Fam A̱ka̱wa̱tyia̱ a̱byin [[Naijeriya]] hu. A̱lyoot Tyap ka, kikya yet a̱lyoot sa̱la̱u sot zwályiat a̱ja. Tyap ja yet a̱lyem [[A̱tyap]] ka. Á̱ ka ngyei nji ''Katab'' ku ''Kataf'' (nang [[A̱kpat|A̱kpat wu]] a̱ni). Á̱ ka lyen nji ma̱ng lyulyoot zwályiat ghyáng nji nang ''Sholyia̱'' (á̱ ma ndyuut, ''Sholyio'' ku ''Sholio'' ma̱ng ''Moro'a'', nang yei A̱kpat wu). Zwályiat njhyang nji ja yet: ''[[A̱byin Fantswam|Fantswam]] (Kafanchan)'', ''[[Gwoot]] (Gworok, Kagoro)'', ''Takad'' (Attakar), ''Tyap proper'' (Maba̱ta̱do), ''Tyeca̱rak'' (Kacecere) ma̱ng ''Tyuku'' (nang á̱ si̱ ma ndyuut ''Tuku'') a̱ni. Ma̱ng si̱sak Blench (2008), [[A̱lyem Jhyo|Jhyo]] ji — ji̱ byia̱ ma̱ng á̱niet lyiat ba̱ lan shi a̱ni — li á ngyei kak tangka̱i Tyap ghyang hwa (shimba á̱niet lyiat nji ba vwuon di̱ sa nwap).<ref name=p>"[https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Plateau_languages web Central Plateau languages]" (di̱n Shong).</ref>
 
==Mak mi̱ mak tai a̱balilyem Tyap ==
Lyilyim mak mi̱ mak mkpa̱t nfi̱k mat á̱ fi̱k si̱sak nang tai hu tsi̱tsak Kaje (Jhyuo), Katab (Tyap) ma̱ng Kagoro (Gwoot) shi si̱ tat a̱ni mi̱ [[Lyulyoot Swadesh|Lyulyoot swáng a̱lyiat Swadesh]] ku shyia̱ ma̱ng á̱ngga 118 á̱si̱ ''a̱tsatsak a̱gban a̱lyiat'' a̱ni, Wurm (1971), ma̱ a̱lyiat nggu na si̱ tak nyia̱, mkpa̱t nfi̱k na tyai nyia̱ nnwap a̱tat na lyiat a̱balilyem a̱lyem a̱nyiung hwa.<ref>Wurm, S. A. (1971). "Papuan Linguistic Situation. Current Trends in Linguistics". Sebeok, T. (Ed.). Vol. 8. Pp. 541–65. The Hague.</ref>
